pr_title: Refactored code, added new Button class, reduced rerenders
pr_body:
#23 stated a lot of software design issues and issues with performance and also the architecture of the codebase
while this PR does not aim to be a direct resolution to that issue, this PR does fix a lot of problems mentioned in it

# This should open your editor and then you can look for both commits and move them close to each other
$ git rebase -i 363793c
# So in your editor you'll have something like this
pick 19986b6 Created generic Game class
pick efddd14 Create class Spike in spike.py
pick 44c92ca created Generator class in generator.py
# Which you'll rearrange to
pick 19986b6 Created generic Game class
s 44c92ca created Generator class in generator.py
pick efddd14 Create class Spike in spike.py
# Then exit the editor and you'll be taken into another editor to edit both commit messages and you can 
# then combine them into one and delete the other so you'll have one commit message and the 
# other would be empty then exit
$ git rebase --continue # should be the final trick.

pr_title: Fix Bug in win check for gameType divided_screen
pr_body:
Steps to reproduce:

1.  Play the gametype of correclty placing the cats, which is divided_screen
2.  In that gameType when the oddCats are to be placed to the left, Even if you place the cats correctly you won't have a win.

Reason:
It was checking for the evenCats on the left even though oddCats are to be checked.
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 1239762116, 'comment_body': 'Why this check?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 23, 12, 34, 2, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'chimosky', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1239764316, 'comment_body': '`correctly_placed` is never true in your checks so the placement would always be wrong regardless, anything `% 2 == 0` should be even, not odd.

Did you test this?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 23, 12, 36, 32, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'chimosky', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1239778386, 'comment_body': "I did test this, If you look at `line 352`, Correctly_placed is declared as true, now if the user places cats incorrectly in any of the possible cases it is making it false.

In that divided game, sometimes odd count cats are to be placed at right or some other time it has to be placed at left.

Before it was only checked for the right side. 
 
`if self.sides[0] == SideType.ODD` tells whether the odd message is on the right or left, and then accordingly it's checking.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 23, 12, 49, 53, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jriyyya', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1239813346, 'comment_body': "I can see that `correctly_placed` was declared as True earlier, I was referring to your checks.

`correctly_placed` starts out as True and gets assigned False regardless of the outcome and both checks are different but both assign `correctly_placed` to False and that's not right as both checks shouldn't equate to False, anything `% 2 == 0` equates to that thing being even and in your else statement it equates to False.
So this means `correctly_placed` is always False regardless, you can use print statements to verify.

The multiple checks isn't necessary as something is even when `% 2 == 0` is True and False otherwise.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 23, 13, 21, 45, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'chimosky', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1239840429, 'comment_body': "Um so I think you are getting something wrong here.
First we are checking this `if self.sides[0] == SideType.ODD:`, so through this we will know if odd message is on right or left, now let's say it's `true` then odd cats are should be placed at left,

then, 
1. `if cat.x < alloc.width // 2 and catsCount[cat.cat_id-1] % 2 == 0 :`
this if condition will check if the cats that are **placed at left has a count of even or not**, and if any of those cat has a even count we are making correctly_placed as false, as cats of *odd* count should be present there, and it is breaking out of the for loop as next iterations are unnecessary to be checked.

now the next if condition,

2.  `if cat.x > alloc.width // 2 and catsCount[cat.cat_id-1] % 2 != 0:`
checks if any cats that are **placed at right is odd,** and if so correclty_placed is made false, as even count cats should be present there.

The need for both of the if condition is that, if i remove 2nd if condition and I place all the cats to the right, it will make it as a win, regardless of the count.

the else condition is for when the odd message is on right and it just switches both of these cases for right and left.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 23, 13, 46, 29, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jriyyya', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1239883552, 'comment_body': '![Screencast from 2023-06-23 15-17-10](https://github.com/sugarlabs/classify-cats/assets/16203834/ac8e0510-17f0-4f94-bbc6-f68659c16482)

This is the outcome of your change.

@quozl can you test?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 23, 14, 21, 58, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'chimosky', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1239895218, 'comment_body': "Isn't this what it should be expected?

The green cat has an odd count, and placing one of its cats on the even side is a loss.

I guess we are deciphering the question differently.

`classify each kind of cat as even and odd`
since **each kind** was specified, the cats having odd count, count being counted on basis of color and not the cats placed on any section.
", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 23, 14, 31, 59, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jriyyya', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1239898323, 'comment_body': "If you place all the Green, yellow and blue cats on left, as they have an odd count of 3, 3 and 1 respectively and red cat on right as it's count is 2 which is even you will have a win. 

This is what i thought the gameplay was. ", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 23, 14, 34, 35, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jriyyya', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1240833420, 'comment_body': "Yes you're right, I got confused and it's been a while I ran this activity.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 24, 14, 50, 18, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'chimosky', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1240833453, 'comment_body': 'We should add a help to the activity.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 24, 14, 50, 57, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'chimosky', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_title: Refactored code and created separate classes for Ball, Brick and Bat
pr_body:
Hi @chimosky and @sourabhaa please review, This PR refactors and restructures the code for this activity. I was trying to implement the powerups but as it turned out it would've been very difficult to do so with the existing code structure. The ball was coded in as a single variable, its velocity and states as well. also the code had redundant variables and many variables were being redeclared every function call which made the entire process hectic.

Thus, I ended up refactoring the code in a manner where implementing the powerups will be easier. I will be having a separate PR for powerups sometime later this month as I will be working on classify-cats now.

If they're parts of this function that's generic then let those be left and this class can be inherited and any function redefinition can happen if necessary.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 12, 22, 17, 44, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'chimosky', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1227298679, 'comment_body': 'This gets imported in this commit but then the file gets added in a different commit, either move the addition here or move the usage to the addition.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 12, 22, 20, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'chimosky', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1227299791, 'comment_body': 'Please add a license here too.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 12, 22, 20, 52, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'chimosky', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1227300523, 'comment_body': 'No need for the parentheses here.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 12, 22, 21, 27, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'chimosky', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1227301838, 'comment_body': 'Could you move these close to the function definition as it makes it more readable.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 12, 22, 23, 12, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'chimosky', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1227301970, 'comment_body': 'No need for the parentheses.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 12, 22, 23, 24, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'chimosky', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1227302962, 'comment_body': 'This could be changed to `if self.y < (self.initial - self.path_length):`', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 12, 22, 24, 57, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'chimosky', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1227306461, 'comment_body': 'No need for the parentheses around `len`.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 12, 22, 31, 11, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'chimosky', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1227308916, 'comment_body': "I'm curious, why the `guys` param?", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 12, 22, 35, 16, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'chimosky', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1230653483, 'comment_body': 'checks collision with each guys and returns True if game over, false otherwise
', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 15, 8, 39, 1, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jriyyya', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1230668866, 'comment_body': "The class is not supposed to inherit from, when I say it's generic I mean that it acts as all the game types itself depending upon the keymap input which it takes.

Keymap also helps the class to handle the event function accordingly in a modular manner thus eliminating a reason for any inhertied classes to implement their own run function or even inherit from it in the first place.
", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 15, 8, 49, 3, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jriyyya', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1233263629, 'comment_body': "The loop for the keys should come after the event has been detected and not the other way around, are you supposed to be handling all KEYDOWN events every iteration? That could be memory intensive, how about you handle a particular event when it's detected?", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 18, 11, 53, 58, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'chimosky', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1233264586, 'comment_body': 'How come this has two loops when the old code had just one?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 18, 11, 59, 10, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'chimosky', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1233266524, 'comment_body': "You could squash both commits as that's easier.

Adding your personal contact details to the license isn't a great idea, please remove it.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 18, 12, 1, 39, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'chimosky', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1236775418, 'comment_body': 'Can you please tell me how can I squash ( [19986b6](https://github.com/sugarlabs/make-them-fall-activity/pull/25/commits/19986b60de562997dcf5821c806ff3bedf27efdd) and [44c92ca](https://github.com/sugarlabs/make-them-fall-activity/pull/25/commits/44c92cab94c42b5b31f171f6420e1d5a92a2259f) ) these two commits, I tried but it is getting real messy', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 21, 10, 35, 47, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jriyyya', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1236856274, 'comment_body': "I've made a commit related to this [0b6a605](https://github.com/sugarlabs/make-them-fall-activity/pull/25/commits/0b6a605c6ecef4bc87a1582e08c5375c2fa8c4d3)", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 21, 11, 37, 8, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jriyyya', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1236858510, 'comment_body': "I'm using list comprehension for flattening the 2-D array which was taken as an input in the constructor", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 21, 11, 38, 52, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jriyyya', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1237398575, 'comment_body': "You can run an interactive rebase on the parent commit and in this case that's 363793c so it'll look something like this;
```bash
# This should open your editor and then you can look for both commits and move them close to each other
$ git rebase -i 363793c
# So in your editor you'll have something like this
pick 19986b6 Created generic Game class
pick efddd14 Create class Spike in spike.py
pick 44c92ca created Generator class in generator.py
# Which you'll rearrange to
pick 19986b6 Created generic Game class
s 44c92ca created Generator class in generator.py
pick efddd14 Create class Spike in spike.py
# Then exit the editor and you'll be taken into another editor to edit both commit messages and you can 
# then combine them into one and delete the other so you'll have one commit message and the 
# other would be empty then exit
$ git rebase --continue # should be the final trick.
", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 21, 18, 13, 3, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'chimosky', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1237401281, 'comment_body': 'Yes, I should have phrased that differently.

I meant we should change the variable to something more generic like sprite.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 21, 18, 15, 50, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'chimosky', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1237406917, 'comment_body': "Yes, basically in the loop, row was added while looping through the keymap but now you're also looping through the row and adding each item in row when in your loop you just added the rows.

Why change to doing it that way?", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 21, 18, 19, 10, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'chimosky', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1237408706, 'comment_body': 'Thanks!', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 21, 18, 21, 6, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'chimosky', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1238229143, 'comment_body': 'Thanks Ibiam, I should have asked beforehand, I spent a lot of time figuring this out while completely forgetting that I can change the order of the commits in the rebase ðŸ˜… ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 22, 9, 1, 25, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jriyyya', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1238241424, 'comment_body': 'I want a single array, so before I was adding array to an array, but because of list comprehension, I am having array inside an array, so through the other for loop I am flattening that array.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 22, 9, 12, 15, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jriyyya', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1238245517, 'comment_body': 'So is Sprite name fine? Should I change this everywhere guy name is used', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 22, 9, 15, 51, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jriyyya', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1239773484, 'comment_body': "You're welcome, trying things out first before asking is a great way to learn.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 23, 12, 44, 43, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'chimosky', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1239776819, 'comment_body': 'Okay.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 23, 12, 48, 10, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'chimosky', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1239778394, 'comment_body': "Yes sprite is fine if you can't think of anything else, turtleart uses sprites that's why it came to my mind.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 23, 12, 49, 53, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'chimosky', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_body:
## Commit 1
### [Fixed highscore loading, now shows updated highscore at game_over screen](https://github.com/sugarlabs/classify-cats/commit/c1f37a3d3d77f38374b4c50e7c1d5a87330b5741)
This commit aims to fix the issue with how the highscore is loaded which doesn't let it update in contrast to the current score 
This buggy behavior is shown in the below screenshot and has been fixed by this commit.

![Screenshot 2023-02-17 152841](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/96080203/223096294-c343e200-6027-4f3c-a5c7-afe602e3f3be.jpg)

## Commit 2
### [Added showing current score after every game, and a bonus score for tâ€¦](https://github.com/sugarlabs/classify-cats/commit/08ae06724e59619f72f83e1cd1c393175b332fbb)
This commit adds a message to the end screen of each screen, the current score is displayed at the end of every game now. 
Also in the ```Rows``` game mode, there was no reward for the reaction time of correctly selecting the cats before the time was over
So I have added bonus score for answering correctly by adding the remaining time to the player's score.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/96080203/223105028-31c7a214-06c6-48cf-9145-12a5234dc8bc.png)


## Commit 3
### [Fixed grammatical errors in messages](https://github.com/sugarlabs/classify-cats/commit/784d7e637f63c2b919c4a00911c9a4e256309a80)
Fixed a few grammatical errors in the messages displayed in game

## Commit 4
### [fixed the win check for placing cats - based on type instead of countâ€¦](https://github.com/sugarlabs/classify-cats/commit/d43dbab52f288544c8788b9a11fa1d05027d584f)

This aims to fix the win check condition of the `DIVIDED_SCREEN` game mode.
The game was intended to check if the cats with even no of the same cats were on one side of the screen
for eg: place all green cats on the left of the screen if the total count of green cats is even
and so on
but the check was for if on the left side of the screen there were even no of cats regardless of their type and odd count on the right. This has been changed by this commit
This commit finally fixed how the game checks the win condition

pr_title: Bug Fix for the perfect Score
pr_body:
## Overview
Fixed a bug : Perfect score was shown incorrectly due to incomplete colortest

## Steps to replicate bugs
1. Play the game and make it so that the stick lands on a white pixel
2. Notice that the game shows +1 perfect even though we didn't make the stick land at the red spot in the center of a pillar

## Expected Behavior
The game is only supposed to show perfect when we land on a red pixel 

## Cause 
The colortest for perfect score was done in the following manner 
```
if(colortest[0] == 255):
```
which only checks the Red value in the RGB spectrum 
so even a whitespace would match the check as Red value of white is also 255 as is for any other color with R value of 255

## Fix
To fix this I have simply set the colortest to check all r g and b values of the rgb spectrum in the following manner
```
if(colortest[0] == 255 and colortest[1] == 0 and colortest[2] == 0):
```

this ensures red and only red pixels trigger the perfect score 

## Screenshot
![screenshot1](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/96080203/218313969-79ac251f-071b-4d0b-a127-aec8e602d5a5.jpg)

> Here is a demonstration of how the bug plays out
